<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15915</anchor> <rss>jms-00CD.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CD</addr>  <route>jms-00CD.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">weak successor algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">algebraic set theory</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. We may define the <em>induced weak successor algebra</em> <tex>X ^s</tex> to have the same carrier object as <tex>X</tex>, with the successor map <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ s _{ X ^s } }} { X }</tex> defined to be the following composite:
  <center><img src="resources/fde1fe39c00d37c528f74ffdbc515db3-web.svg"/></center>  and with the algebra map <tex>{ T X ^s } \xrightarrow{{ \alpha _{ X ^s } }} { X ^s }</tex> defined as follows:
  <center><img src="resources/388a9d5ed5c889741a26879c822bf4b9-web.svg"/></center></p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15916</anchor> <rss>jms-00CF.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00CF</addr>  <route>jms-00CF.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced successor algebra on an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>15917</anchor> <rss>jms-00CD.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CD</addr>  <route>jms-00CD.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">weak successor algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">algebraic set theory</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. We may define the <em>induced weak successor algebra</em> <tex>X ^s</tex> to have the same carrier object as <tex>X</tex>, with the successor map <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ s _{ X ^s } }} { X }</tex> defined to be the following composite:
  <center><img src="resources/fde1fe39c00d37c528f74ffdbc515db3-web.svg"/></center>  and with the algebra map <tex>{ T X ^s } \xrightarrow{{ \alpha _{ X ^s } }} { X ^s }</tex> defined as follows:
  <center><img src="resources/388a9d5ed5c889741a26879c822bf4b9-web.svg"/></center></p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>15918</anchor> <rss>jms-00CE.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CE</addr>  <route>jms-00CE.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Unitality of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link> <tex>X ^s</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">unital</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>We are trying to check that the following morphism is an identity:</p>  <center><img src="resources/d4c2905dc6994f8b69cbf0a5e5d024cb-web.svg"/></center>  <ol>    <li>We unfold the definition of the algebra map <tex>\alpha _{ X ^s }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/df063430eb2e85989d87430775a41266-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>We use the unit law for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/2bce4749b0870142b6d4c68a12929f32-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>Finally, we use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> is inverse to <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/e9eb3146cf77a42b60370734008be59b-web.svg"/></center>    </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>15919</anchor> <rss>jms-00CG.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CG</addr>  <route>jms-00CG.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Associativity of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link> <tex>X ^s</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">associative</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>We are trying to check that the following identity holds:</p>  <center><img src="resources/fca710980cea4fd18d0bd797a04d4771-web.svg"/></center>  <ol>    <li>      We will start on the right-hand side. We first unfold the definition of the algebra map.
    
      <center><img src="resources/0c008ed534dee916062a417c0c19f570-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> inverts <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/e9248589a4935cccb66656d90dcdb9ca-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We use the associativity of the monad <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/fc70c2ca090b9edab801e7d286621490-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Folding the definition of the algebra map, we have the desired cell.
      <center><img src="resources/7058de84ab6505fcdd739bb36c1f0695-web.svg"/></center>    </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>4</crumb></trail> <anchor>15920</anchor> <rss>jms-00CH.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Corollary</taxon> <addr>jms-00CH</addr>  <route>jms-00CH.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link> is a successor algebra</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link> <tex>X ^s</tex> is a <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   Because it is <link href="jms-00CE.xml" type="local" title="Unitality of the induced weak successor algebra">unital</link> and <link href="jms-00CG.xml" type="local" title="Associativity of the induced weak successor algebra">associative</link>.
</block>  </mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15921</anchor> <rss>jms-00C9.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C9</addr>  <route>jms-00C9.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Successor algebra</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">algebraic set theory</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>. A <em>(weak) successor algebra</em> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> is defined to be a (<link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">weak</link>) <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">algebra</link> <tex>X</tex> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> together with a morphism <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ s _{ X } }} { X }</tex> in <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> called the <em>successor map</em>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15922</anchor> <rss>jms-00C8.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C8</addr>  <route>jms-00C8.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Weak algebra for a monad</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We shall refer to an <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebra</link> for the underlying endofunctor of a monad as a <em>weak algebra</em>, following <link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">Joyal and Moerdijk</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15923</anchor> <rss>jms-00CH.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Corollary</taxon> <addr>jms-00CH</addr>  <route>jms-00CH.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link> is a successor algebra</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link> <tex>X ^s</tex> is a <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   Because it is <link href="jms-00CE.xml" type="local" title="Unitality of the induced weak successor algebra">unital</link> and <link href="jms-00CG.xml" type="local" title="Associativity of the induced weak successor algebra">associative</link>.
</block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15924</anchor> <rss>jms-00CG.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CG</addr>  <route>jms-00CG.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Associativity of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced weak successor algebra">induced weak successor algebra</link> <tex>X ^s</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">associative</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>We are trying to check that the following identity holds:</p>  <center><img src="resources/fca710980cea4fd18d0bd797a04d4771-web.svg"/></center>  <ol>    <li>      We will start on the right-hand side. We first unfold the definition of the algebra map.
    
